defaultIs Government policy and regulatory action by the defaultOffice of Rail Regulation (ORR) in relation to safety at level crossings adequate? What more should the Government and ORR do?default&#xa0;default6.1
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe rail sector has engaged positively with Department of Transport in an effort to give level crossing issues greater prominenc
defaulte in the Highway Code and in the written driving test.  It is recognised that there are limitations to the amount of space / time that can be alloca
defaultted in the Code or during tests.
default 
defaultIn addition t
defaulthe
default excellent guidance for level crossing users produced by ORR
default 
defaultis available on its website but is not obviously accessible to most road users
default – who are unlikely to be looking for advice from the railway regulator
default.  It is suggested that it should be made more widely available, and promoted more positively
default by other agencies
default.
default&#xa0;
default6.2
default&#xa0; 
defaultORR ha
defaults
default looked at crossings both generally and at the individual crossing level and have perhaps not adequately considered the strategic view in terms of how crossings are kept up to date with 
defaultthe 
defaultchanges to HMRI/ORR requirements/guida
defaultnce and 
defaultthe 
defaultelimination of early Victorian arrangements
default.
default&#xa0;
default6.3
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Department for Transport could also do more to encourage collaboration between the highways/roads agencies with the railways to share the responsibility for managing level crossing risk.
