default7default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHow defaultshould the legislation governing level crossings be updated?default&#xa0;default7.1
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn 2008 The Law Commissions of England and Wales, and of Scotland, started work on identifying whether changes to level crossing legislation were needed, and if so, what they should include. The
defaulty specifically remitted work on public road signs to RSSB (which is in progress) and they worked closely with both road and rail sectors to agree proposals for change.  There was particular emphasis on the potential of the AXIAT model to help drive public 
defaultroad crossing closures forward, and the need for statutory co-operation protocols between rail and highway authorities. A number of dates for publication of a draft bill have been announced and have been passed, and it is suggested that this may be due to 
defaulta lack of political support for such changes.  Given that the existing body of laws is well out-of-date and does not help motivate all the various parties to work together effectively this delay is to be deplored.  It is hoped that the process may be resta
defaultrted 
default&#xa0;
default7.2
default&#xa0; 
defaultRSSB 
default(
defaultand Network Rail
default)
default have 
defaultexpressed 
defaultconcerns over one aspect of the possible changes
default;
default that of the removal of the 
defaultL
defaultevel 
defaultC
defaultrossing Order procedure. Although this is intended to remove a level of 
defaultgovernment administration, it is also likely to remove a level of certainty that has served the railway well for the past 50 years. The 
defaultprincipal fear
default is that it will become very difficult, if not impossible
default,
default to prosecute a motorist for an offence at a lev
defaultel crossing.
default&#xa0;
default8default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHow should public awareness of safety at level crossings be improved?default&#xa0;default8.1
default&#xa0; 
defaultA number of methods are available, and some have been referred to already. Educating schoolchildren and other young people about the dangers present at level crossings is 
defaultimportant and resources should continue to be allocated to do this, especially in areas near crossings.  There is a particular need to emphasise to the public that trains cannot stop as quickly as a car can.  Emerging research suggests that elderly 
defaultpeople 
defaultare also particularly at risk
default if they do not understand how to use crossings effectively
default, so they need to be included as a target audience.  Finally, there is a definite need to make sure that road signs communicate the appropriate message, and when the cu
defaultrrent group of research projects have been completed, it is hoped that DfT, and Parliament, will support any changes indicated.
default&#xa0;
default9default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultConcluding remarksdefault&#xa0;default9.1
default&#xa0; 
defaultWhile the UK level crossings are demonstrably the safest in the European Union, it remains the case that it
default is only constant vigilance and reinforcement of the messages about how to use level crossings, enforcement of the rules by authorities, and the never ending search for more cost effective ways of providing effective protection at level crossings that will
default maintain that position. In that respect RSSB is proud to play its part in supporting the industry in the way that we do.
